subSubSection.paragraph:
Cephalic plate with shallow median anterior depression in the shape of a letter ‘Y’ with long branches oriented antero-laterally (
Fig. 5
). Scapular plate without any ridges (
Fig. 6
). Paired plates I and II shortest along antero-caudal median body axis and transversally deepen in the anterior third (
Figs 7–10
). Terminal plate with two posterolateral incisions and without faceting (
Figs 11–13
). Cephalic, neck, scapular, median 1, median 2 and terminal plates undivided (
Figs 1–2
, 
6–13
). Both median plates 1 and 2 have laterally joined two lateral platelets (one on each side) equally wide as the lateral margins of adjacent median plates but subsequently tapering towards the lateral margins, which are approximately on the level of lateral margins of the adjoining plates (scapular plate, paired plates I and II) (
Figs 8, 10
). Median plate 3 (
Figs 12–13
) and ventral plates (
Fig. 3
), absent. Anterior and posterior boundaries of dorso-lateral plates and platelets well marked with the exception of barely visible boundary between cephalic and neck plates (
Figs 2
, 
5
), anterior boundaries in the first pair of lateral platelets (
Figs 2
, 
8
), and first median plate (
Figs 2
, 
7–8
). Lateral margins of dorso-lateral plates and platelets and the edges of leg plates on I–III pair of legs marked less distinctly (
Figs 2
, 
4–6, 9–10
) than those in terminal plate (
Figs 2
, 
12–13
). Vague, elongated 
pulvinus
on outer side of each leg just above the leg plate present (
Figs 1
, 
17
). Cuticular bars on inner leg sides just above bases of claws, distinct (
Figs 3
, 
16, 18–19
).

Claws on each leg well developed, basal portion straight, bent in the last third (broadest region), and continued with fluent arc to the apex (
Figs 16, 18–19
). External claws slightly shorter than internal and claws on the hind legs are the longest. Internal claws in all legs with a well-developed rather protruding spur, oriented downwards (longer on hind legs), which is connected to the main claw at between the second fifth and a half the height (spur connection positions in the first and fourth pairs of legs 4.9 μm and 5.6 μm from the claw base respectively; thus 46% of the claw length). All external claws without spurs (
Figs 16, 18–19
). Spine or papilla on the first three pairs of legs, absent. Drop-shaped papilla with rounded apex and dentate collar with mostly slender, triangular, sharp teeth having single tip and unequal base (0.4–1.5 μm) present on the fourth pair of legs. Tooth height (0.6–1.7 μm; the base of each tooth mostly shorter than the height with one exception) and very unequally spaced (some adjoining teeth in contact and others more remote—maximally 3.1 μm) (
Figs 17–19
).

